---
import SiteLayout from '../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro';

const schema = [
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "Article",
    "headline": "Chocolate Tempering Guide",
    "description": "Complete chocolate tempering guide covering why tempering matters, cocoa butter crystal forms, tabling, seeding, microwave methods, temperature charts, troubleshooting bloom, couverture vs compound chocolate, making bonbons, dipping technique, and essential tools.",
    "url": "https://28grams.vip/chocolate-tempering-guide",
    "author": {
      "@type": "Organization",
      "name": "28grams"
    }
  },
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is couverture vs compound chocolate?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Couverture chocolate contains a high percentage of cocoa butter, requiring tempering for a proper finish. Compound chocolate replaces cocoa butter with other vegetable fats and does not need tempering."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Why is my chocolate streaky and grey?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "This is known as 'bloom'. Fat bloom happens when cocoa butter separates and crystallizes on the surface due to improper tempering or temperature swings. It is safe to eat but lacks the snap and shine."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Can I fix bloomed chocolate?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Yes, bloomed chocolate can be easily fixed by simply re-melting and properly re-tempering it to re-establish the correct crystal structure."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What are the essential tools for tempering chocolate?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "The absolute essentials are an accurate digital thermometer (infrared or probe) and a spatula. For the tabling method, a large marble slab and a bench scraper are also required."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is the best way to dip truffles?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Use a specialized dipping fork. Submerge the center completely, lift it out, tap the fork gently on the edge of the bowl to remove excess chocolate, and slide it onto parchment paper."
        }
      }
    ]
  }
];

const mainEntityArray = schema[1].mainEntity;
---

<SiteLayout
  site="28grams"
  title="Chocolate Tempering Guide"
  description="Complete chocolate tempering guide covering why tempering matters, cocoa butter crystal forms, tabling, seeding, microwave methods, temperature charts, troubleshooting bloom, couverture vs compound chocolate, making bonbons, dipping technique, and essential tools."
  canonical="https://28grams.vip/chocolate-tempering-guide"
  schema={JSON.stringify(schema)}
>
  <style>
* { margin: 0; padding: 0; box-sizing: border-box; }
.page-wrapper {
  font-family: 'Inter', sans-serif;
  background: #0a060a;
  color: #e0d0d8;
  min-height: 100vh;
  --card-bg: #120c10;
  --border-color: #2a1820;
  --accent-color: #C2185B;
  --text-secondary: #888;
}

code, .mono { font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace; }

.hero { text-align: center; padding: 48px 24px 24px; background: linear-gradient(180deg, #1a0a14 0%, #0a060a 100%); }
.hero h1 { font-size: 2.4rem; font-weight: 900; color: #fff; margin-bottom: 6px; }
.hero h1 span { background: linear-gradient(135deg, var(--accent-color), #ff6b9d); -webkit-background-clip: text; -webkit-text-fill-color: transparent; background-clip: text; }
.hero p { color: #666; font-size: 0.95rem; max-width: 560px; margin: 0 auto; }
.main { max-width: 1000px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 32px 20px 40px; }

.formula-card, .guide-card {
  background: var(--card-bg);
  border: 2px solid var(--border-color);
  border-radius: 16px;
  overflow: hidden;
  margin-bottom: 32px;
}
.card-header {
  display: flex;
  justify-content: space-between;
  align-items: center;
  padding: 16px 20px;
  background: #150d12;
  border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-color);
}
.card-header h2 { font-size: 1.2rem; font-weight: 700; color: #fff; margin: 0; }
.card-content { padding: 20px; }
.card-content p { color: #c8b8c0; line-height: 1.6; margin-bottom: 12px; }
.card-content ul { padding-left: 20px; margin-bottom: 12px; color: #c8b8c0; line-height: 1.6; }
.card-content li { margin-bottom: 6px; }

.content p { font-size: 0.9rem; color: #777; line-height: 1.8; margin-bottom: 14px; }

.recipe-section { margin-bottom: 40px; padding-bottom: 24px; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-color); }
.recipe-section:last-of-type { border-bottom: none; }
.recipe-header { display: flex; align-items: baseline; gap: 12px; margin-bottom: 16px; }
.recipe-header h3 { margin: 0; font-size: 1.3rem; color: var(--accent-color); }
.recipe-meta { font-size: 0.85rem; color: var(--text-secondary); background: #1a1015; padding: 4px 8px; border-radius: 4px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); }

.recipe-info-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(200px, 1fr));
    gap: 16px;
    margin-bottom: 16px;
}
.recipe-info-card {
    background: #150d12;
    padding: 12px 16px;
    border-radius: 8px;
    border: 1px solid var(--border-color);
}
.recipe-info-label {
    font-size: 0.75rem;
    color: var(--text-secondary);
    text-transform: uppercase;
    font-weight: 600;
    margin-bottom: 4px;
}
.recipe-info-value {
    color: #e0d0d8;
    font-size: 0.95rem;
    line-height: 1.4;
}

.faq-list { margin-top: 24px; }
.faq-item { margin-bottom: 24px; }
.faq-q { font-weight: 700; color: #fff; margin-bottom: 8px; font-size: 1.05rem; }
.faq-a { color: #777; font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.6; }

@media (max-width: 600px) {
  .hero h1 { font-size: 1.8rem; }
  .recipe-header { flex-direction: column; gap: 4px; }
}
  </style>

<div class="page-wrapper">
<div class="hero">
  <h1>Chocolate Tempering <span>Guide</span> 🍫</h1>
  <p>Complete chocolate tempering guide covering why tempering matters, cocoa butter crystal forms, tabling, seeding, microwave methods, temperature charts, troubleshooting bloom, couverture vs compound chocolate, making bonbons, dipping technique, and essential tools.</p>
</div>

<div class="main">
  <h2 style="font-size: 1.8rem; font-weight: 800; color: #fff; margin: 40px 0 20px;">The Fundamentals</h2>

  <div class="formula-card">
    <div class="card-header">
      <h2>Why Tempering Matters</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="card-content">
      <p>Cocoa butter is polymorphic, meaning its crystals can set in different structures. Tempering ensures the chocolate solidifies into the optimal structure (Form V), which gives it its desirable qualities.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><b>Snap:</b> A crisp, clean break when bitten or snapped.</li>
        <li><b>Shine:</b> A glossy, smooth finish instead of a dull, matte appearance.</li>
        <li><b>Shelf Life & Stability:</b> Prevents fat bloom (white streaks) and raises the melting point, preventing it from melting instantly on your fingers.</li>
        <li><b>Shrinkage:</b> Allows chocolate to shrink slightly as it cools, making it possible to release bonbons from molds.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="formula-card">
    <div class="card-header">
      <h2>Form V Crystals</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="card-content">
      <p>There are six types of cocoa butter crystals, labeled Form I through Form VI. Form V (Beta) crystals are the goal.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><b>Forms I to IV:</b> Unstable crystals. They have low melting points, yield soft or crumbly chocolate, and eventually transform into Form VI, causing bloom.</li>
        <li><b>Form V:</b> Highly stable, providing gloss, snap, and an excellent mouthfeel.</li>
        <li><b>Form VI:</b> Formed over months of storage or due to blooming. Extremely hard and high melting point.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>The tempering process melts away all crystals, cools the chocolate to encourage Form V formation, and gently reheats to eliminate any unwanted Form I-IV crystals.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2 style="font-size: 1.8rem; font-weight: 800; color: #fff; margin: 40px 0 20px;">Temperature Charts</h2>

  <div class="recipe-section">
    <div class="recipe-header"><h3>Dark Chocolate</h3><span class="recipe-meta">Temperatures</span></div>
    <div class="recipe-info-grid">
      <div class="recipe-info-card"><div class="recipe-info-label">1. Melt</div><div class="recipe-info-value">113-122°F (45-50°C)</div></div>
      <div class="recipe-info-card"><div class="recipe-info-label">2. Cool</div><div class="recipe-info-value">82-84°F (28-29°C)</div></div>
      <div class="recipe-info-card"><div class="recipe-info-label">3. Working Temp</div><div class="recipe-info-value">88-90°F (31-32°C)</div></div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="recipe-section">
    <div class="recipe-header"><h3>Milk Chocolate</h3><span class="recipe-meta">Temperatures</span></div>
    <div class="recipe-info-grid">
      <div class="recipe-info-card"><div class="recipe-info-label">1. Melt</div><div class="recipe-info-value">104-113°F (40-45°C)</div></div>
      <div class="recipe-info-card"><div class="recipe-info-label">2. Cool</div><div class="recipe-info-value">81-82°F (27-28°C)</div></div>
      <div class="recipe-info-card"><div class="recipe-info-label">3. Working Temp</div><div class="recipe-info-value">86-88°F (30-31°C)</div></div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="recipe-section">
    <div class="recipe-header"><h3>White Chocolate</h3><span class="recipe-meta">Temperatures</span></div>
    <div class="recipe-info-grid">
      <div class="recipe-info-card"><div class="recipe-info-label">1. Melt</div><div class="recipe-info-value">104-113°F (40-45°C)</div></div>
      <div class="recipe-info-card"><div class="recipe-info-label">2. Cool</div><div class="recipe-info-value">79-81°F (26-27°C)</div></div>
      <div class="recipe-info-card"><div class="recipe-info-label">3. Working Temp</div><div class="recipe-info-value">82-84°F (28-29°C)</div></div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2 style="font-size: 1.8rem; font-weight: 800; color: #fff; margin: 40px 0 20px;">The 3 Methods</h2>

  <div class="formula-card">
    <div class="card-header">
      <h2>1. The Seeding Method</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="card-content">
      <p>The most common and foolproof method for beginners, utilizing pre-tempered chocolate to "seed" the formation of Form V crystals.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><b>Melt:</b> Melt 2/3 of your chocolate over a double boiler to the melting temperature.</li>
        <li><b>Seed:</b> Remove from heat and stir in the remaining 1/3 of finely chopped, tempered chocolate (the "seed").</li>
        <li><b>Cool:</b> Stir continuously until the chocolate drops to its target cooling temperature and the seed pieces melt.</li>
        <li><b>Warm:</b> Gently reheat the chocolate to its working temperature to melt out unwanted low-temperature crystals.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="formula-card">
    <div class="card-header">
      <h2>2. The Tabling Method</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="card-content">
      <p>The classic professional technique requiring a marble slab, creating a visually impressive and very efficient temper.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><b>Melt:</b> Melt all the chocolate to the correct melting temperature.</li>
        <li><b>Table:</b> Pour 2/3 of the melted chocolate onto a clean marble slab.</li>
        <li><b>Agitate:</b> Using a bench scraper and offset spatula, spread the chocolate out and fold it back into itself repeatedly to cool it down to around 82°F, forming a "mush."</li>
        <li><b>Combine:</b> Add the cooled, thickened chocolate back into the remaining 1/3 warm chocolate. Stir thoroughly until it reaches working temperature.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="formula-card">
    <div class="card-header">
      <h2>3. The Microwave Method</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="card-content">
      <p>A quick, small-batch method that bypasses the melting and cooling stages entirely by maintaining the chocolate's existing temper.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><b>Chop:</b> Finely chop tempered chocolate and place in a plastic bowl (glass retains too much heat).</li>
        <li><b>Heat:</b> Microwave at 50% power in 15-second intervals.</li>
        <li><b>Stir:</b> Stir vigorously between each interval, even if it doesn't look melted.</li>
        <li><b>Monitor:</b> Stop heating when the chocolate is mostly melted with a few lumps. Stir until the residual heat melts the remaining pieces. Do not exceed the working temperature!</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2 style="font-size: 1.8rem; font-weight: 800; color: #fff; margin: 40px 0 20px;">Techniques & Tips</h2>

  <div class="formula-card">
    <div class="card-header">
      <h2>Making Bonbons & Molds</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="card-content">
      <p>Using polycarbonate molds is essential for shiny, perfect bonbons.</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Polish the mold cavities with cotton balls or microfiber cloth before use. Even invisible residue dulls the finish.</li>
        <li>Fill the cavities with tempered chocolate, tap the mold to remove air bubbles, then invert it over your bowl to dump out the excess, leaving a thin shell.</li>
        <li>Scrape the top clean and let the shell set before piping in your filling (ensure filling is no warmer than 80°F to prevent melting the shell).</li>
        <li>Cap the bonbons with more tempered chocolate, scrape clean, and let set before unmolding.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="formula-card">
    <div class="card-header">
      <h2>Chocolate Dipping</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="card-content">
      <p>For dipping truffles, fruits, or cookies, preparation is key.</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Ensure your centers are room temperature. Cold centers will shock the chocolate and may cause it to crack later as the center expands.</li>
        <li>Use a dipping fork (or a regular fork with the middle tines broken off) to submerge the center.</li>
        <li>Tap the fork on the side of the bowl to let excess chocolate run off. Draw the bottom of the fork over the bowl's edge to remove the "foot" (the pool of chocolate that forms at the base).</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2 style="font-size: 1.8rem; font-weight: 800; color: #fff; margin: 40px 0 20px;">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq-list">
    {mainEntityArray.map((faq) => (
      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">{faq.name}</div>
        <div class="faq-a">{faq.acceptedAnswer.text}</div>
      </div>
    ))}
  </div>
</div>
</div>
</SiteLayout>
